\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{pgfplots}
\pgfplotsset{compat=1.18}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \begin{tikzpicture}
        \begin{axis}[
            ybar,
            bar width=0.2cm,
            ymin=0,
            ymax=110,
            ylabel={Improvement Over Control \%},
            xlabel={Model},
            xtick=data,
            xticklabels={
                Blend (13,6,6B),
                GPT3.5 (175B),
                Vicuna+ (13B),
                ChaiLLM (6B)
            },
            legend pos=north west,
            symbolic x coords={
                Blend (13,6,6B),
                GPT3.5 (175B),
                Vicuna+ (13B),
                ChaiLLM (6B)
            },
            nodes near coords,
            nodes near coords align={vertical},
            ymajorgrids=true,
            grid style=dashed,
            height=8cm,
            width=10cm,
            enlarge x limits=0.2,
            legend style={at={(0.5,-0.1)},anchor=north,legend columns=-1},
        ]
            \addplot[fill=white,hatch=xhatch] coordinates {
                (Blend (13,6,6B), 100) 
                (GPT3.5 (175B), 80) 
                (Vicuna+ (13B), 20) 
                (ChaiLLM (6B), 10)
            };
            \addplot[fill=white,hatch=horizontal] coordinates {
                (Blend (13,6,6B), 0) 
                (GPT3.5 (175B), 0) 
                (Vicuna+ (13B), 0) 
                (ChaiLLM (6B), 0)
            };
            \legend{Engagement, Retention}
        \end{axis}
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{Model performance comparisons, setting the baseline as Pygmalion 6B. Each model is assigned to 5,000 unique new users, graphs report the day 30 retention and engagement improvement with respect to the baseline.}
    \label{fig:model_performance}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Packages**: The `pgfplots` package is used for creating the plot.
- **Axes Configuration**: The `ybar` option is used to create vertical bars. The `bar width` is set to `0.2cm` to make the bars more visible.
- **Data Points**: The data points for each model's performance are specified in the `\addplot` commands.
- **Legend**: The `legend` is placed at the top left corner of the plot.
- **Nodes Near Coords**: This option places the values of the bars directly on top of them.

This code will generate a bar chart similar to the one provided in the image. Adjust the values in the `\addplot` commands if you need to change the specific improvements over control percentages.

